And then your compiler will optimize it to this:<p><pre><code>    int token_length = strlen(token);

    // Just get this out of the way now; no need to dawdle
    // (because the length of a token is generally known)
    if (token_length != strlen(input)) {
        return false;
    }

    // No need to worry about mismatched buffer lengths at this point
    for(int i=0; i<token_length; i++) {
        if (token[i] != input[i]) {
            return false;
        }
    }
    return true;
</code></pre>
And all of a sudden the timing attack is back.<p>You <i>cannot</i> write a constant-time function in portable C / C++, and trying to do so is a fool&#x27;s game.
